ll fat tarn cause new unem\nployment. The vicious circle will\nwiden and today's recession will be\ncome more serious.\n\u201cThe AFIi-CIO is determined that\nthis must not happen.\n\u201cTo that end the ASTi-GIO Execu\ntive Council has authorized the oon\nt (Continued on Page Foot)\nMeany to Head\nILO Advisers\nAFL-CIO Preaidant George Meany\nwill head ASTrCIO advisers to the\nlate spring conference of the Interna*\ntiohal tabor Organization at Geneva,\nSwitzerland; George P. belaaey is\nU. 3. workers' delegate.\nOthers nominated by Meiny are\nEmil Bleve, chairman at the executive\nboard of the Textile Workers; Pres.\nHarry C. Bates at the Bricklayers;\nPresident David I. McDonald at the\nSteelworkers; Vlee President leader\nNagler of the Garment Workers; and\nPresident Eugene Frasier of the\nUnited Transport Service Employee.\nA group of five ABTrOO officials\nwill go to Havana, Cuba next month\nfor the dedication of a new tourist\nhotel built with funds invested by the\npension fuhd of the Cbban Gastro\nnomic\u2014hotel and restaurant, that is\u2014\nworkers. >i /t.-V*\".\nVice Presidents Rieve, Paul L.\nI Phlllps. and A. Philip Randolph to\ngether with Director Michael Roes of\nthe Iirtl, A\u00a3(*to. Dcpt- and Seraiftno\ni Romualdi, AVKcdO Inter-American\nrepresentative, will attend.\nThe invitation to the ceremonies\nr was brought to the Executive Coun\nCU by repreeentativee of the Cuban\nj The foapcoelbillty of til* labor\nmovement to dam for the \u201cout-of\nplant needs\" of union members \"ii\nevery, bit as important \"as caring for\nthe in-plant' needs,\u201d according to\nJoseph A.. Beiroe, chairman of the\nAFIj-CSO Community Services Com\nmittee y-h. 'Y\u201e*V\nMr. Beime stressed this responsi\nbility in an article appearing in the\ncurrent issue, of the \u201cIUD Digest,\u201d:\npublished quarterly by the Industrial\nUnion Department of the labor Mem\ntlon. He la a:member of the AJpI*-CJO\nXxecuttve Couacil and president of the\nOnmrtiimlraticpe Worfrero of America.\n;V -v-..\nT\nOffer Plan io v\nHalt Slump\nAFL-CIO spokesmen have urged an\nimmediate program to halt the reces\nsion and put the .jobless millions back\nto work.\n.In an interview on the American\nProadcasting Network radio program,\n\"As We See It\u201d, Hyrtian Bookbinder,\nof the AFL-CIO legislative depart\nment, and Nat Goidflnger, AFL-dO\neconomist, called for:\n1\u2014Public works, Including public\nhousing, -hospitals, libraries, schools,\nand flood control.\n2\u2014Increasing the personal Income\ntan exemption by $100.\na\u2014Increasing levels and duration of\nunemployment compensation pay\nments.\n4\u2014 Extending coverage of the mini\nmum wage law to workers in retail\nstores, laundries, hotels and restaur\nants, and increasing the minimum to\n$1.25 an hear.\n5\u2014 Improvement of social security\nby increasing old age benefits and pro\n(Continued on Page Four)\nPay Hike i^&r:\nWith 4% million persons jobless,\nthe unemployment compensation in\nsurance law needs Improvement to aid\nthe jobless and to provide the econ\nomy with a needed stimulus.\nSenator John F. Kennedy (D*\n\u25a0Mass.), and Hep. Eugene 1. McCarthy\n(D* Minn.), mode this statement In\na discussion of bills they have intro\nduced to Increase unemployment com\npensation payments to 50 per cent of\na worker\u2019s wage and extend payments\nfor as long as SO weeks. They were in\nterviewed on the ABTr-GIO piddle\nservice radio program, \"Washington\nReports to the People.\u2019\u2019\n'\"Some states are now paying as low\nas $28 and $30 a week to unemployed\nworkers,\u201d Ketinedy asserted. \"You\ncan\u2019t live on that. Recent statistics\nshow that it costs a single woman $51\na week as a minimum in some of oar\nnwjorcities. And most of the people\ni' T'*\n(Oenttnued ea Pngs rear)\u25a0-\n3 The \"Community Services Commit\ntee wUdt heheada 1* charged with the\nresponsibility of maintaining organ\nized labor\u2019s relationships with the\nvoluntary and public agencies In the\nhealth, welfare and recreation field;\nPredicting \u2018hignlfleant advances\u201d\nin benefits for union members ae the\nresult of collective bargaining nego\ntiations in the neat few years\u2014Includ\ning tbs guaranteed animal wage, the\nshorter. werfc weak and better retire\nment and, health programs Mr.\nBairae reminded the MSermovement\n>s;\n!y J/\nys-'\nTO USE DEPRESSION TO\nCURTAIL PAY HIKES -i?M\nThe' AJlrCXO iDept of Research\nwants that some employers will at\ntempt to capitalize ton the recession to\ndeny unions reasonable wage in\ncreases in 1958.\nHie fact is, the department added\nin its monthly Collective Bargaining\nReport, that mow than 4 million\nworkers will receive wage increases in\n1958 ranging firoin. 7 to 13 cents an\nhour. 2..\nIt added that tea limited extent the\ngeneral trend in collective bargaining\nhinges on the depth of the current re\ncession, but that If an economic up\ntorn appears by early sunnier, wage\nIncreases cl from 10 to 15 cents sa\nboor are likely.\nHie bulk of wage increases in 1957,\nthe report says, were 10 or more cents\nan hour, with about one-third calling\nfor 13 at more cents.\nThe 1957 increases were needed in\nhuge part to make up for the rise in\nliving costs, but were sufficiently\nlarge in many cases to provide \"for\nsome reasonable real gain\" beyond\nthe catch-up range.\nBargaining In 1958, the report adds,\nis tied at the moment to the reces\nsion. If the downturn gains momen\ntum it will'have a limiting effect on\nwage increases \"even though wage in\ncreases are most vitally needed in\nsuch a period to stimulate the econ\nomy.\u201d V x..\u2019\n\"However, the report'declare*; If\neconomic conditions ahow Improve\nment by late spring or early simmer\nthe economic difficulties In the earlier\nmonths \"should not have a depressing\neffect op the year\u2019s bargaining re\nsults.\u201d\nSome employers, the report says,'\n\"undoubtedly will try to capitalise on\nthe economic recession by citing it to\nunions as a reason for \"restraint\u2019 on\nwage increases. But unions will not be\nled into abandoning reasonable wage\ndemands on the ground of the general\neconomic downturn.\u201d\n(Continued on Page Four)\nNewspaper Strike\nWon in St. Paul\nA 48-day strike of editorial and\nmechanical unions against the St Paul\n.Dispatch and Pioneer Press ended\nwith wage increases ranging from $8\nto $B per week over a two-year period.\nThe newspapers signed new agree\nments with the Typographical Union,\nthe Mailers, Stereotypers, Machinists\nand the St Paul Newspaper Guild.\nDuring the strike, which started\nDec. 17, the unions published 29 edi\ntions of a special strike paper, the 9t\nPaul Sentinel. The final edition of the\nSentinel ran 40 pages and had a cir\nculation of 41,000.\nGIVING UP OR GIVING\nly RUTH TAYLOR\nWhen I was little, we used to ask each other \u201cWhat are you\ngoing to give up for Lent?\u201d And we used to feel very virtuous\n\u2014at first\u2014-over our self- abnegations.\nBut I think with adults, there is something more important\nthan just \u201cgiving up\u201d things for Lent\u2014admirable as the custom is.\nAnd that is to plan on what we are going to give of ourselves dur\ning the Lenten season. V\nI don't mean just the time we give to our churches, or to con\ntemplation of our lives, of our mistakes and ways in which to\ncorrect them\u2014but in giving of ourselves to others.\nLent is a good time in which to get caught up- on ..the little\nkindnesses, the thoughtful things we always meant to do, and\nnever quite found the time for, the expressions of what we meant\nto do and say\u2014but never did.\nIt is not enough for us to pray \u201cMake us quick to the needs\nof others\u201d, without really trying to do something about them.\nWhat this kind of giving means is not the mere sharing of material\nthings, but of putting ourselves aside long enough to recognize\nthe aspirations and perceive the feelings and need of others.\nlYiking the time to be courteous and kind to all whom we meet\nin our daily life is not time-taken from our duties. We know how\nwe are affected by the manners of others and how our day is\nbrightened and our work made easier when we meet with a friend\nly, smiling person. Surely we can give that much this Lenten sea\nson?\nTaking the time to really listen tp the people to whom we\ntalk gives us as much as we are giving. .The boost in spirits that\ncomes from, having somebody friendly enough to listen to our\nproblems we already know. Surely we can give that much to others.\nTaking time to visit or write or call those who are lonely in\nheart, ill or depressed, may not seem like much of a gift\u2014but it\nmay help more than wq know and give new courage and will to\nendure to those who need it.\nLent is a time for gratitude\u2014and there is no better way to\nshow our gratitude for God\u2019s infinite mercies to us, than by giving\nof ourselves in the service of others.\nThe Summit County Labor New\u00a7 is the only\nIiabor Paper published in Summit County. It\ncovers a field that you can reach in no other way.\n(Political Advertising\n\nCards Folders Ballots\nCAMPAIGN LITERATURE\n\n'.4 ,.V\n920 SOlfTH HIGH STREET PO 2-1110\nV\nWant Better Pensions\nAlso in Negotiations\nOpening in March\nHaving learned the hard way that many doctors tack on addi\ntional charges above surgical insurance fee schedules, the United\nRubber Workers (URW) union has set a full payment surgical\nplan as one df the major goals in coming pension and insurance\nnegotiations.\nBy unanimous vote, 160 delegates from URW locals in United\nStates and Canada adopted a pension and insurance bargaining\nprogram in the wind-up session of a two-day conference in Cleve\nland s Hotel Carter late last week. URW President L. S. Buck\nmaster presided at the conference.\nThe program, adopted after hours\nTaft-Hartley Is\nInvoked Again\nAt O\u2019Sullivan\nThe National Labor Relations Board\nhas aimed another Taft-Hartley Act\nroundhouse swing- at the Rubber\nWorkers in behalf of the O\u2019Sullivan\nRubber dorp., which braes of its\nproduct as \u201cAmerio&\u2019s No. 1 heel.\u201d\nA hearing is scheduled in Winchest\ner, Va, next Tuesday on a complaint\nfiled by NLRB eneral Counsel Jerome\nJ D. Fenton charging the union with\nunfair practices in continuing to pic\nket and boycott O\u2019Sullivan after los\ning an NLRB decertification election\narising from the firing of strikers.\nIt\u2019s against the law, Fenton\u2019s com\nplaint asserts, for former O'Sullivan\nemployes to picket the company plant\nafter being fired and losing the\nelection in which, under Taft-Hartley,\nthey were not allowed to vote.\nBut picketing of O\u2019Sullivan Rub\nber Oorp. and the nation-wide con\nsumers\u2019 boycott of that company's\nproducts is an exercise of the right\nof free speech as guaranteed by the\nFirst Amendment of the U. S. Con\nstitution, United Rubber Workers\ncontend.\nThat was the URW answer this\nweek to file charge filed by the com\npany.\nThe union\u2019s answer was filed with\nNLdtB, which set a hearing for Tues\nday.\nThe union, fay |Joi\u00ab\u00bbting and by sup\nporting the consumer boycott, is\n(Continued on Fnge Four)\nAKRON LABOR COUNCIL\ning of Akron Labor Ouancti, AFL\n,CK>, is scheduled te.be held in the\nauditorium of Goodrich Local No.\n5 at 708 Sooth Marin Street on\nMonday night, Mar. 24th. The\nmeeting will be called to order at\n8:00 o\u2019clock by L. W. tfoitolau^fa\nThis aanoameemtnt Boaotitulae the\nofficial notification of the mnntlBg\nto all delegatee and other persona\ndeririBg to bo praoit\nThe Executive Beard of the\nOh\u2014oil will held tin next regntai\nborineae meetleg in the WBmer\nTSte Men\u2014Ini Borne on Thnre\nday evening, March 20th.\nREUTHER SAYS ROMNEY IS\n\u2018QUICK CHANGE ARTIST- ti\nPresident Welter p. Reutter at the\nAuto Workers ran into a little diffl\nniulty when he attempted to\non the testimony of George Romney,\npresident at American Motors and the\nAutomobile Manufacturers Associa\ntion, before the Senate Anti-Trust\nand Anti-Monopoly subcommittee.\nRomney, before the subcommittee,\nwas sharply critical of the UAW bar\ngaining program and maintained that\ndeclining sales in recent weeks wens\ndue to the union\u2019s proposal Cor a re*\nbate to car buyers.\n\u25a0anther captained hie AfUeioty\ngrew eat at the Cast that of all aaoter\n.v\ni'\\.\n-tV 1\" V v V\nof full discussion and dozens of\nchange* originating: on the flow, he--'\ncornea a recommended guide for URW\nnegotiators. v\"\nFirst 1058 pension and insurance\nnegotiations are. scheduled to begin\nwith Goodyear Tire A Rubber Co.\nsometime in March. The URW is ex-\npected to serve pension and insurance\nagreement reopening notices on other\nmajor companies and a number of\nsmaller companies within the next\nseveral months.\nA. major demand, as spelled oat la A\nthe adopted program, calls for a fUH\npayment company-paid comprehen\n**ve surgical and obetetrlcal benefit\nschedule for workers ami their de\npendents and pensioners and their de\npendents.\nExperience has shown the need for\nsuch a Jull payment program,. Paul f\nE. Bowers, URW pension and insur\nance director, told the delegates. f\nThe present URW negotiated suig\nical plans have a fee schedule which\npays up to 8250. In thousands of\ncases, Bowers explained, the surgeon's\n(Continued on Page Four)\nHome Building\nShows Cain\nNonfarm housing starts rose to\n69.000 in January, compared with\n62.000 in December and 63,000 in\nJanuary a year ago, the U. S. Labor\nDepartment's Bureau of Labor Static-\ntics reported.\nThe month\u2019s increase of 11 per cent\n\u2014which followed a more than sea- V\nsonal decline hi December\u2014was shar-\ned about equally by private and public\nbousing. Preliminary reports indicate\nthe gain occurred primarily in the\nSouth and West,\nPrivate housing starts increased\nfrom 60,800 in December to 64,200 In\nJanuary, and were at a seasonally ad\njusted annual rate of 1,030,000\u2014a lit\ntle above the 1 million average In\nthe fourth quarter of 1957, and the\nhighest annual rate since last August.\nThus, the improvement shown in pri- V\nvat* starts in the latter half of 1957\nextended into January of this year. J\nStarts in public hnmriwg projects\ntotaled 4,800 in January\u2014a fourfold\nincrease from December. About two--\nthirds of the January 1958 public\ntotal were in projects begun under the\narmed services (Oapehart) program.\ned himself as qtricfe rhaiign artist.\u2019* v\n\u201cOn Jan. 28, 1957\u201c Rsuther \u2018f\nplained, \u201clie expressed himself em\nphatically as being opposed to Indus- ff\ntrywide bargaining. On Sept 20,1907, v\nhe asserted himself in favor of Indus-\ntrywide collective bargaining, Just M.\nemphatically. On Fab. 7, 1968, he did 1\nanother about-face and declared he\nwould oppose Industrywide bargaining,\nwith all Us strength. .4^%^\n\u201cOn Sept 14, 1987, he came out M;\nfoursquare for a consumer rebate at\n\u2022<.Vv","height":"25848","width":"20196"}}
